**$mod+shift+(comma and less than)** key

how ever, I don't know how to name (comma and less than) key when shift is pressed. 

further, is there any table we can source the name of all keys? some of them are really tricky e.g., (left bracket and left curly bracket)</description><pubDate>Thu, 26 Sep 2013 10:28:15 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://faq.i3wm.org/question/2597/what-is-the-name-of-shiftcomma-and-less-than-key/</guid></item><item><title>Answer by vandannen for &lt;p&gt;I want to define a key binding on&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;$mod+shift+(comma and less than)&lt;/strong&gt; key&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;how ever, I don't know how to name (comma and less than) key when shift is pressed. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;further, is there any table we can source the name of all keys? some of them are really tricky e.g., (left bracket and left curly bracket)&lt;/p&gt;
 </title><link>https://faq.i3wm.org/question/2597/what-is-the-name-of-shiftcomma-and-less-than-key/?answer=2599#post-id-2599</link><description>You can use xev for finding the key name. The name does not need to be adjusted when using Shift. </description><pubDate>Thu, 26 Sep 2013 11:45:33 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://faq.i3wm.org/question/2597/what-is-the-name-of-shiftcomma-and-less-than-key/?answer=2599#post-id-2599</guid></item><item><title>Comment by BatmanAoD for &lt;p&gt;You can use xev for finding the key name. The name does not need to be adjusted when using Shift. &lt;/p&gt;
